Grid is a 2-dimensional layout system (rows AND columns simultaneously).

.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr;
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  gap: 16px;
}

Grid vs Flexbox:
• Grid: 2D layouts, page-level structure, complex alignment
• Flexbox: 1D layouts, component-level, distributing space

They work great together — Grid for page layout, Flexbox for components within grid cells.

Custom properties are reusable values defined with -- prefix:

:root {
  --primary: #6C5CE7;
  --spacing-md: 16px;
}

.button {
  background: var(--primary);
  padding: var(--spacing-md);
}

Key features:
• Cascade and inherit like normal CSS
• Can be changed at runtime with JavaScript
• Scoped to elements (not just global)
• Can have fallbacks: var(--color, blue)
• Enable dynamic theming (dark mode) by changing root variables

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .sidebar { display: none; }
}

Modern approach — mobile-first:
/* Base styles = mobile */
.grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }

/* Tablet and up */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
}

Modern alternatives:
• Container queries: @container (min-width: 400px)
• clamp(): font-size: clamp(1rem, 2.5vw, 2rem)
• minmax() in Grid: grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr))

Transitions: Animate between two states on property change.
.btn {
  transition: background 0.3s ease, transform 0.2s;
}
.btn:hover { background: blue; transform: scale(1.05); }

Animations: Multi-step, can auto-play, loop, and reverse.
@keyframes fadeIn {
  from { opacity: 0; }
  to { opacity: 1; }
}
.modal { animation: fadeIn 0.3s ease-out; }

Rule of thumb:
• Transition = simple A→B state changes (hover, active)
• Animation = complex, multi-step, or auto-playing motion

Container queries let components respond to their CONTAINER's size, not the viewport.

.card-container {
  container-type: inline-size;
}

@container (min-width: 400px) {
  .card { flex-direction: row; }
}

Why they matter:
• Components adapt to where they're placed, not page width
• True component-based responsive design
• A sidebar card and a main-content card can have different layouts
• Works with container-name for targeting specific containers

This is the future of responsive component design.

The cascade determines which styles apply when rules conflict:

1. Origin & Importance:
   User agent → Author → Author !important → User !important

2. Specificity:
   Inline > ID > Class > Element

3. Source Order:
   Later rules win when specificity is equal

CSS Cascade Layers (@layer) add a new dimension:
@layer base, components, utilities;

@layer base { a { color: blue; } }
@layer utilities { .text-red { color: red; } }

Layers let you control cascade priority independent of specificity.
